# Introduction
The model is based on the paper ["A STATISTICAL MODEL OF CRIMINAL BEHAVIOR" by M. B. Short, M. R. D'Orsogna, V.B. Pasour, G. E. Tita, P.J. Brantingham, A.L. Pertozzi and L.B. Chayes published in Mathematical Models and Methods in Applied Sciences
Vol. 18, Suppl. (2008) 1249â€“1267](https://www.math.ucla.edu/~bertozzi/papers/M3AS-final.pdf)
---
# Theory Background
The attractiveness of a house to be victimized is based on two assumptions:
- repeat and near-repeat victimization
- broken windows effect
$$A_s(t) = A_s^0 + B_s(t)$$
---
# Model
- MultiGrid with size 50 x 50 (original 128 x 128)
- Uniform distribution of attractiveness
- Burglars tend to "walk" towards more attractive houses
-  Central Parameters
- $\eta$ - Measures neighborhood effect [0 - 1]
- $\theta$ - Dynamic increase of attractiveness
- $\Gamma$ - Rate of burglar generation at each site
